1 (2) “Closed captioning” means a transcript or dialog of the audio portion of
2 a television program that is displayed on a television receiver screen when the user
3 activates the feature.
4 (3) “Closed movie captioning” means the written display of the dialog and
5 certain nonspeech information of a motion picture that is generally delivered to individual
6 patrons on a captioning device in a motion picture house.
7 (4) “Closed–captioning television receiver” means a receiver of television
8 programming that has the ability to display closed captioning, including a television, digital
9 set top box, and any other technology capable of displaying closed captioning.
10 (5) “Open movie captioning” means a transcript or dialog of the audio
11 portion of a motion picture that is displayed on a motion picture screen that cannot be
12 turned off by a viewer.
13 (6) “Public area” means a part of a place of public accommodation that is
14 open to the general public.
15 (7) “Regular hours” means the hours of any day in which a place of public
16 accommodation is open to members of the general public.
17 (b) (1) On request, a place of public accommodation may not fail to keep closed
18 captioning activated on any closed–captioning television receiver that is in use during
19 regular hours in any public area.
20 (2) This subsection does not require a place of public accommodation to
21 make closed captioning available in a public area of the place of public accommodation if:
22 (i) no television receiver of any kind is available in the public area;
23 or
24 (ii) the only public television receiver available in the public area is
25 not a closed–captioning television receiver.
26 (c) (1) A place of public accommodation that is a motion picture house shall
27 provide access to fully operational and well–maintained closed movie captioning technology
28 for the general public for each screening of a motion picture that is produced and available
29 with closed movie captioning as required by Title III of the federal Americans with
30 Disabilities Act.
31 (2) (i) This paragraph does not apply to motion pictures screened fewer
32 than five times from Friday through Thursday in a 7–day period in the motion picture
33 house.
34 (ii) This paragraph applies only to the first 3 weeks after a motion
35 picture premieres in the motion picture house.

